  "text": "The results suggested that exposure to hyperoxia resulted in NQO1 induction and that the resulting increase in total NQO1 activity conferred an increased capacity to reduce DQ to the stable two-electron reduction product, DQH [CITATION_1] . We anticipated that the increase in NQO1 activity would provide greater competition for any DQ reduction occurring via one-electron pathways, thereby providing the hyperoxia-exposed cells with Fig. 5 . Inhibition of normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cell mediated DQH2 oxidation by the mitochondrial electron transport inhibitor KCN. A: concentration of DQ in the medium surrounding normoxic or hyperoxia-exposed cells after incubation with 50 M DQH2 in the presence of 2 mM KCN. In B, peroxidase and H2O2 were added to the medium removed from the cells after the 30-min incubation period. The increase in DQ concentration, as indicated by the arrows, reflects the amount of DQH2 in the medium that was surrounding the cells at the end of the incubation in A. The surface area of cell-coated microcarrier beads (means Ϯ SE in units of cm 2 ) used for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cell studies were 45.0 Ϯ 4.0 and 43.9 Ϯ 6.3, respectively. The data represent the means Ϯ SE for 3 studies each for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells. Fig. 6 . Inhibitor effects on normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cell DQ-mediated ferricyanide reduction rates. The bars represent the DQ-mediated ferricyanide reduction rates (means Ϯ SE) in the presence of DQ (50 M), with no inhibitor additions or with dicumarol (25 M), KCN (2 mM), or dicumarol ϩ KCN (25 M and 2 mM, respectively). The reduction rates were obtained by linear regression of the ferrocyanide concentration vs. time curves, and data obtained without DQ were subtracted as background from the data obtained with DQ, as in Fig. 2 . The surface area of cell-coated microcarrier beads (means Ϯ SE in units of cm 2 ) used for normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells, respectively, were as follows: no additions, 51.4 Ϯ 1.6 and 51.7 Ϯ 2.0; dicumarol, 54.1 Ϯ 2.2 and 50.9 Ϯ 1.7; KCN, 54.8 Ϯ 1.8 and 53.2 Ϯ 2.0; dicumarol ϩ KCN, 51.8 Ϯ 1.8 and 53.0 Ϯ 2.4. The number of experiments carried out with no additions for normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells was n ϭ 20 each, which includes 16 from the 50 M concentration data in Fig. 2 . For the other conditions, the number of experiments for the normoxic and hyperoxia-exposed cells was n ϭ 9 each with dicumarol, n ϭ 11 each with KCN, and n ϭ 9 each with dicumarol ϩ KCN. *Significantly different from normoxic cells with no inhibitor addition; †significantly different from hyperoxia-exposed cells with no inhibitor addition; ‡significantly different from corresponding treatment in normoxic cells (t-test, P Ͻ 0.05).",
